Linux Filesystem Hierarchy Standard (FHS)

Instead of drive letters like C:\
, D:\
 in Windows, Linux uses a single tree structure starting from the /
 (root) directory. This structure is standardized by the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard (FHS).
Directory	Description	Content Example
/
(Root)	The starting point of the file system.	Entire system.
/bin
	Contains basic user commands. (Binary)	ls
, cp
, cat
, bash
/boot
	Contains files needed for the system to boot.	vmlinuz
(Kernel), initrd
, GRUB
/dev
	Contains hardware device files. (Devices)	/dev/sda
(Disk), /dev/tty
(Terminal)
/etc
	The center where system configuration files are located.	/etc/passwd
, /etc/ssh/sshd_config
/home
	The place where users' personal files are stored.	/home/john
, /home/ali
/lib
	Library files needed by programs.	libc.so
, Kernel modules
/mnt
& /media
	Temporarily mounted disks and USB drives.	/media/usb-disk
/opt
	Manually installed 3rd party applications.	Google Chrome, TeamViewer etc.
/proc
	Virtual file system. Holds system info.	/proc/cpuinfo
, /proc/meminfo
/root
	The home directory of the system administrator (root).	Root's private files.
/sbin
	Critical commands used only by the administrator.	iptables
, fdisk
, reboot
/tmp
	For temporary files.	Application caches.
/usr
	Secondary hierarchy. User tools are here.	/usr/bin/python
, /usr/share
/var
	Files whose size constantly changes.	Logs (/var/log
), Website (/var/www
)
